  "prompt": "After demonetization of Rs.500 and Rs.1000 notes, what will happen to old notes?",
  "response": "After the demonetization of Rs. 500 and Rs. 1000 notes in India, which was announced on November 8, 2016, the old notes ceased to be legal tender. Here are the key points regarding the old notes after demonetization:\n\n1. **Exchange and Deposit**: Initially, people were given a limited time to deposit or exchange their old notes at banks. The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) allowed individuals to deposit the demonetized notes into their bank accounts or exchange them for new currency notes.\n\n2. **Deadline**: There was a specific deadline set for the exchange and deposit of these notes. After the deadline, individuals could no longer exchange them in banks.\n\n3. **Withdrawal from Circulation**: The old notes were effectively removed from circulation, meaning they could not be used for transactions after the demonetization announcement.\n\n4. **Limited Use**: Some exceptions were made for certain purposes, like paying for medical expenses, government services, or purchasing tickets on transportation services within a short period after the announcement.\n\n5. **Confiscation Post Deadline**: If individuals did not deposit or exchange their old notes by the established deadline, those notes became worthless, and any possession of them after that was not legally recognized.\n\n6. **Black Money**: The primary goal of demonetization was to target black money, counterfeit currency, and to push for a digital economy. The government aimed to bring unaccounted cash into the formal banking system.\n\n7. **Disposal of Old Notes**: Once collected from the public, the demonetized notes were shredded and destroyed by the Reserve Bank of India as part of the process of retiring them from circulation.\n\nOverall, the demonetization of Rs. 500 and Rs. 1000 notes had significant implications for the Indian economy, led to a cash crunch at that time, and sparked widespread discussions and debates regarding its effectiveness and impact.",
